07:36.119 --> 07:37.920
Great news, ma'am.

07:37.921 --> 07:39.956
Uh, it's more like insanely
amazing news. Go ahead.

07:39.957 --> 07:42.358
Kat found some ironclad
security guarantees for

07:42.359 --> 07:43.868
- our cyberweaponry.
- Cyberweaponry.

07:43.869 --> 07:44.886
President Zaragoza will sign

07:44.887 --> 07:46.363
the extradition
agreement within the hour.

07:46.364 --> 07:48.331
Apologies. I promise this is
enthusiasm, not impertinence.

07:48.332 --> 07:50.038
- Understood.
- That is great.

07:50.039 --> 07:53.169
And insanely amazing.

07:53.170 --> 07:55.938
Ma'am, Miguel Briseño from
the Washington Chronicle is here

07:55.939 --> 07:57.440
- for your interview.
- Mexican bureau chief?

07:57.441 --> 07:59.809
I'll be there in a second.

07:59.810 --> 08:00.810
Details.

08:00.811 --> 08:03.112
- It was all Ms. Sandoval.
- Oh.

08:03.113 --> 08:04.413
Well, let's hear it.

08:04.414 --> 08:06.749
No, I just, uh, asked INR to find

08:06.750 --> 08:08.784
the American cybersecurity
firm that Mexico wants

08:08.785 --> 08:10.887
to contract, Kizlet
Programming, and then I made

08:10.888 --> 08:13.523
a super solid deal with
their CEO, Kenny Fisk.

08:13.524 --> 08:15.791
He guaranteed that
any tech Kizlet shares

08:15.792 --> 08:18.828
will be completely traceable
and can be disabled remotely

08:18.829 --> 08:20.396
at a moment's notice.
CYBERCOM signed off

08:20.397 --> 08:22.398
in, like, five seconds.
It was barely even a thing.

08:22.399 --> 08:25.635
Usually, those private
sector guys, they hate working

08:25.636 --> 08:27.270
- with the government.
- Tell me about it.

08:27.271 --> 08:29.205
So I Facebooked Fisk.

08:29.206 --> 08:31.374
Found he's deep into Neal Stephenson.

08:31.375 --> 08:33.109
That doesn't ring a bell.

08:33.110 --> 08:34.409
Yeah. No. Sci-Fi author.

08:34.410 --> 08:35.678
He wrote Cryptonomicon.

08:35.679 --> 08:37.346
- No.
- Anathem?

08:37.347 --> 08:40.216
- Mm.
- Um, Seveneves.

08:40.217 --> 08:41.250
Wow.

08:41.251 --> 08:43.186
Still no bells? Okay.

08:43.187 --> 08:44.921
Now I know your Christmas gift.

08:44.922 --> 08:48.324
Anyway, Fisk and I were
way in the weeds about

08:48.325 --> 08:50.426
the reconstructed society aboard
the Cloud Ark in Seveneves.

08:50.427 --> 08:54.296
So, now he's pretty much
my little nerd buddy.

08:56.900 --> 08:59.100
It's all about relationships, right?

08:59.835 --> 09:02.438
Good job, Kat.

09:02.439 --> 09:04.939
Thank you, ma'am.

09:05.575 --> 09:07.777
I actually have

09:07.778 --> 09:09.378
some breaking news for you.

09:09.379 --> 09:10.746
Hmm.

09:10.747 --> 09:13.149
President Zaragoza is moments away

09:13.150 --> 09:15.785
from signing an extradition agreement.

09:15.786 --> 09:19.388
Sergio Macias is coming
to the United States.

09:19.389 --> 09:22.191
Did Mexico demand any concessions?

09:22.192 --> 09:24.893
Yes, of course.

09:26.195 --> 09:29.298
We've agreed to relax some of our...

09:29.299 --> 09:31.934
trade provisions around...

09:31.935 --> 09:33.502
cybersecurity software.

09:33.503 --> 09:35.671
Defensive software or cyberweaponry?

09:35.672 --> 09:38.474
I'm not really prepared to
comment about that yet...

09:38.475 --> 09:41.711
Are you concerned that if Mexico
obtains American cyberweapons,

09:41.712 --> 09:44.981
they might fall into
the hands of bad actors?

09:44.982 --> 09:48.484
No, we have faith in
the Mexican government.

09:48.485 --> 09:49.752
Really?

09:49.753 --> 09:51.320
You've had guarantees before,

09:51.321 --> 09:52.755
and yet American guns

09:52.756 --> 09:54.724
have still got into the
hands of cartel members.

09:54.725 --> 09:56.592
Other than trade provisions,

09:56.593 --> 10:00.496
does the U.S. have any
solutions to fight the cartels?

10:00.497 --> 10:02.765
I mean, after all, it is...

10:02.766 --> 10:05.968
government corruption
that allows them to thrive.

10:05.969 --> 10:09.438
We've been advising President Zaragoza

10:09.439 --> 10:12.475
to pursue anti-corruption measures.

10:12.476 --> 10:14.442
And, off the record...

10:21.151 --> 10:23.918
You're not wrong.

10:24.720 --> 10:26.855
Excuse me?

10:27.657 --> 10:29.592
We're never gonna beat the cartels

10:29.593 --> 10:32.995
as long as Mexican government
officials stay on their payroll.

10:32.996 --> 10:35.031
What more can the U.S. do?

10:35.032 --> 10:36.666
Mexico is our neighbor

10:36.667 --> 10:40.169
and one of our most reliable
allies and trade partners.

10:40.170 --> 10:42.071
We can't just...

10:42.072 --> 10:45.441
force them into rooting out corruption.

10:45.442 --> 10:49.111
It's like having a best friend
who won't stop robbing banks.

10:49.112 --> 10:52.782
We are doing everything we can,

10:52.783 --> 10:54.817
but...

10:54.818 --> 10:58.521
thankfully, there are
tough reporters like you

10:58.522 --> 11:01.223
who are holding the Mexican
government accountable.

11:01.224 --> 11:02.825
Because ultimately,

11:02.826 --> 11:05.394
I think it just might
be the Fourth Estate

11:05.395 --> 11:07.762
that brings about change.

